**Resources:**

* Raspberry Pi (2,3,4,5, Zero, Zero 2W)  
* SD card compatible with your Pi (for example, Pi 4 uses a microSD)  
* SD/microSD card reader

**Part I \- Imaging the microSD card for the Pi**

| ![][image16] | Open the Raspberry Pi Imager If you don’t have it, you can download it here \-  [https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/](https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/) |
| ----- | :---- |
| ![][image17] | Press "CTRL+Shift+X" to access a hidden menu. Select the following: Set Hostname to **FirstName.LastName\_Pi** Set Username and Password to whatever you want Configure WiFi to your Home's WiFi & Password WiFi Country \- **US** Set Locale Settings to **America/Denver** Skip first-run Wizard |
| ![][image18] | Choose an OS (note, Raspberry Pi OS Lite is terminal only) \- **Raspberry Pi OS (32-bit) \- Debian Bullseye** is recommended. Flash the SD/microSD card with the image you wanted. When finished, put the SD/microSD card into your Pi. |
| **![][image19]** | When it finishes, put the microSD card into the Raspberry Pi and power it on. Connect the following: HDMI micro to HDMI cable to your capture card. Ethernet cord to the Cisco switches on your table. Keyboard and mouse. |

**Part II \- Play around with this and see what it can do**

* Get a thermal camera or thermometer to measure the temperatures.   
* Complete the following stress tests. **Make a chart of the temperatures**.  
  * Idle Use: Do nothing.  
  * Normal Use: Browse the internet and watch YouTube.  
  * Gaming: Play Tux Racing or other Linux games.  
  * Heavy Use: Run the program ‘stress’ on the Pi.

**How to receive credit**:

* Show me that you successfully set up your Raspberry Pi.  
* Show me your temperature recordings.  
* Answer the following questions:  
  * What processor architecture does a Raspberry Pi use? How is that different from your Dell computers?  
  * What are the benefits of using ARM CPUs?  
    * Why did Apple switch their Macbooks to ARM?   
    * Why do all phones and tablets use ARM?  
  * What is a SBC ?
